"Here are the answers to the questions:\n\n***Question 1: \"How likely is it that Bond will escape from Le Chiffre?\"***\n1. Not very likely\n\nThe passage indicates that Bond is trapped and outgunned, and that Le Chiffre is in control. Although Bond is able to evade the first gunman, he is ultimately unable to escape or defend himself effectively, and is left feeling \"puny and impotent\". This suggests that his chances of escape are slim.\n\n***Question 2: \"How suspenseful do you find this passage to be?\"***\n6. Very suspenseful\n\nThe passage is suspenseful because it starts off as a relaxing and intimate scene (Bond preparing for dinner with Vesper), but quickly turns into a violent and intense confrontation. The reader is left wondering what will happen next, and the fact that Bond is outgunned and trapped adds to the tension and uncertainty. The use of words like \"burst in\", \"guns drawn\", and \"puny and impotent\" also contributes to the suspenseful atmosphere."